As artificial intelligence reshapes labor markets, companies increasingly face pressure to take public stances on automation and its societal implications. This study examines visible service automation, focusing on cases where robots replace human labor in consumer-facing contexts. Using an experimental design with 187 Instagram users in Türkiye, the study investigates how advocacy stance influences consumer reactions and corporate reputation. The findings highlight the role of psychological reactance, issue involvement, and service visibility in shaping consumer evaluations of corporate social advocacy related to automation.
